log-processing-mechanism.html.title: Log Processing Mechanism
log-processing-mechanism.html.body:
Log Processing Mechanism
Figure  1  Log system architecture
The log data flow in  Figure 1  is described as follows:

Collecting logs
On the device side, the dlogd process invokes the log driver to collect logs on the non-control CPU, and the sklogd and slogd processes collect logs on the control CPU.
On the host side, the sklogd and slogd processes collect user-mode and kernel-mode logs.

Transmitting logs
Logs on the device side can be transmitted to the host side through the IDE-daemon-device and IDE-daemon-host modules.
The dlogd and slogd processes on the device side write the collected logs to their respective shared memories. Log threads mounted to the IDE-daemon-device module are sent to the IDE-daemon-host module on the host side.

Saving logs to files
Logs on the device side are recorded in log files whose names start with  device-0  by IDE-daemon-host. Logs on the host side are recorded in log files whose names start with  host-0  by slogd. IDE-daemon-host starts the TCP/IP thread and sends host logs to Mind Studio.
The host records logs in log files in customized compression mode. You can view the log information in Mind Studio, but cannot view logs directly through the log files. The log information is displayed as garbled characters when you directly open a log file.
To change the log level, run the IDE-daemon-client command. For details, see  Setting the Log Level.

log-levels.html.title: Log Levels
log-levels.html.body:
Log Levels
This topic describes log levels and level definitions.
Table  1  Log levels

Log Level

Definition



ERROR

Common error level. Logs at this level record the following errors:
Unexpected data or eventError with large-scale impacts but can be processed by a moduleError restricted within a moduleError that slightly affects other modules, for example, a creation failure of a statistics task Error that causes an invocation failureIncorrect service logic. The information about the error status and the possible causes of the error are recorded.


WARNING

Warning level. The system status is inconsistent with the expected one, but the system running is not affected.


INFO

Information level. The information about the normal running of the system is recorded. 


DEBUG

Debug level. Logs of this level record debugging information for R&D engineers or maintenance personnel to locate faults.


EVENT

Event level indicates the most critical logs of the entire system, for example: The calculation of the entire network is started, completed, or terminated abnormally, the memory is insufficient, or the PCB temperature is too high.

A log example is as follows:

The log format is as follows:
[Level] ModuleName(PID,PName):DateTimeMS LogContent
Table  1  Log field description

Field

Description



Level

Log level: ERROR, WARNING, INFO, DEBUG, or EVENT


ModuleName

Name of the module that generates the log


PID

Process ID


PName

Process name


DateTimeMS

Time when the log is printed, in yyyy-mm-dd hh:mm:ss.SSS


LogContent

Detailed log information of each module






 NOTICE:The log formatting character string % must be correctly used. To print  %, use the %% format, which is consistent with the printf rule.Otherwise, logs cannot be properly printed.

setting-the-log-level.html.title: Setting the Log Level
setting-the-log-level.html.body:
Setting the Log Level
Currently, you can set the log level in the following three ways:

Set the log level on the Mind Studio page.
In the  Log  window on the Mind Studio page, click    in  Log List. In the  Config Log Level  dialog box that is displayed, set the log level and click  OK.
The log level configuration in the  System  area applies globally. The log level configuration in the  ModuleList  area applies by module. If the global log level is set, the module-level log level cannot be set. To set the module-level log level, disable the log level setting in the  System area, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Disabling the global log level setting

Run the command on the server to set the log level.
Log in to the server as the Mind Studio installation user, run commands  export  LD_LIBRARY_PATH=~/tools/che/ddk/ddk/uihost/lib  and  export  PATH=$PATH:~/tools/che/ddk/ddk/uihost/bin  in sequence to set environment variables, and run the global or module-level log level setting command.
You can also log in to the host server as the  HwHiAiUser user and run the global or module-level log level setting command. (Only the PCIe scenario is supported.)

To set the global log level, run the following command:
IDE-daemon-client --IP address of the host server:Port number --log 'SetLogLevel(0)[level]'
level  can be set to  error,  info,  warning, or  debug.

To set the level of a specific module, run the following command:
IDE-daemon-client --IP address of the host server:Port number --log 'SetLogLevel(1)[moduleName:level]'
level  can be set to  error,  info,  warning, or  debug.
moduleName  can be set to a module, such as  slog,  dlog, or  cce.

To set the event log level, run the following command:
IDE-daemon-client --IP address of the host server:Port number --log 'SetLogLevel(2)[enable/disable]'
enable: Enables the event log level setting.
disable: Disables the event log level setting.



 NOTE:~/tools  is the default  toolpath  setting, which can be customized during Mind Studio installation. You can view the value of  toolpath in the  scripts/env.conf  file. You can run the  find / -name 'env.conf'  command to view the location of the  env.conf  file in the  script directory.  


Modify the configuration file on the server to set the slogd and dlogd log levels.
For details about the configuration file, see  Log Configuration.
After modifying the configuration file, log in to the host server as the  HwHiAiUser user, log in to the device server using SSH, and restart the slogd, dlogd, and IDE-daemon-host processes.

Log in to the host server, go to the  /usr/local/HiAi/driver/tools  directory, and restart the slogd process by running the  pkill slogd;./slogd &  command.
Log in to the host server, go to the  /usr/local/HiAi/driver/tools  directory, and restart the IDE-daemon-host process by running the  pkill IDE-daemon; ./IDE-daemon-host &  command.
Log in to the device server and restart the slogd process by running the  pkill slogd; /var/slogd >/dev/null &  command.
Log in to the device server and restart the dlogd process running the  pkill dlogd; /var/dlogd >/dev/null &  command.


 NOTE:For the developer board, log in to the server and restart a process by running the  pkill  Process name; /var/Process name  >/dev/null &  command .

what-do-i-do-if-a-log-file-fails-to-be-u.body:
What Do I Do If a Log File Fails to Be Uploaded to Mind Studio Due to the Incorrect Format?
Symptom
The format of the log data block is incorrect. As a result, the log data block cannot be uploaded to the Mind Studio.
Cause Analysis
The last data block in the log file is incorrect and the file size is greater than 256k.
Solution
Log in to the host and delete the log files of the latest date from the /var/dlog directory.

Overview
Mind Studio provides an efficient, easy-to-use, and flexible tool Profiling targeting the multi-node and multi-module heterogeneous system on the host and device. Currently, the tool supports multi-card and multi-chip scenarios. This tool quickly identifies key performance bottlenecks and provides suggestions on performance optimization, hence ensures the ultimate performance of your product.
Mind Studio can collect, analyze, and display the performance data of hardware and software in graphical or command line mode. The overall process is as follows:

Configure the data to be profiled, including the hardware and software performance data.
The hardware performance data includes the performance monitor unit (PMU) events on the control CPU, PMU events on the task schedule CPU, PMU events on the AI CPU, and performance data of peripheral devices.
The software performance data refers to the performance data of modules such as HiAI Engine, the offline model inference engine (OME), and the runtime and task schedule (RTS).

Profile the performance data.
Configure the connection between Mind Studio and the host before profiling the performance data.

View the performance analysis results.
On the Mind Studio GUI, performance analysis results are displayed in the following three dimensions:  Summary,  Timeline, and functions (including  AI CPU Function  and  Control CPU Function).

 NOTE:Before running the Profiling tool, ensure that:  

The non-root user folder in the environment where Profiling runs has the 750 permission.  
The host connected to the device has the permission to run a compiled instance, that is:  
Permission to access and execute the dependent library: Access the path where the dependent library is located as the current user and query whether the dependent library can be executed by the current user.  
Permission to check the compiled instance: After running the process orchestration instance, switch to the project path in  ~/HIAI_PROJECTS/workspace_mind_studioto  check whether the instance can be executed.

configuring-data-to-be-profiled.html.body:
Configuring Data to Be Profiled

Double-click the *.mind  file in the Mind project.
On the process orchestration page that is displayed, click the  Profiling  icon, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Profiling icon

In the  Profiling  dialog box that is displayed, configure the configuration items in the  Hardware,  Software, and  Connection areas to specify the modules whose performance data needs to be profiled and the profiling interval.

Set the  Hardware  parameters.
Figure 2  shows the profiling attributes that can be configured for the hardware.
Figure  2  Hardware configuration area
Table 1  describes the details of the  Hardware  parameters.
Table  1  Hardware configuration parameters

Parameter

Description



Control CPU Profiling

Whether to enable profiling for the control CPU of the NPU. When this parameter is set to ON, the PMU event on the control CPU is profiled. Currently, the default events are 0x11 and 0x8, where 0x11 indicates the number of cycles executed by the CPU and 0x8 indicates the number of executed instructions.


TS CPU Profiling

Whether to enable profiling for the AI task schedule (TS) CPU. When this parameter is set to ON, the PMU event on the TS CPU is profiled. Currently, the default events are 0x11 and 0x8, where 0x11 indicates the number of cycles executed by the CPU and 0x8 indicates the number of executed instructions.


AI CPU Profiling

Whether to enable profiling for the AI operator CPU (different from the AI core CPU). When this parameter is set to ON, the PMU event on the AI CPU is profiled. Currently, the default events are 0x11 and 0x8, where 0x11 indicates the number of cycles executed by the CPU and 0x8 indicates the number of executed instructions.


CPU Sampling Intervals(ms)

PMU event profiling interval of the control CPU, TS CPU, and AI CPU. The default value is 20 (ms).


AI Core Profiling

Processing unit responsible for the scalar, cube, and FP AI computation. Task-based and sample-based AI core profiling is supported. Currently, the default events are 0x3, 0x8, 0x9, 0xe, 0x3a, 0x3b, 0x4a, and 0x49. 0x3 indicates the number of executed cube instructions, 0x8 indicates the number of executed vector instructions, 0x9 indicates the number of executed scalar instructions, 0xe indicates the total number of instruction cycles, 0x3a indicates the number of scalar read requests for the UB, 0x3b indicates the number of scalar write requests for the UB, 0x4a indicates the number of cube int instructions, and 0x49 indicates the number of cube FP instructions. In task-based mode, the performance data is profiled by task, while in sample-based mode, the performance data is profiled at a fixed interval.


Peripheral Profiling

Whether to enable profiling for the peripherals. Currently, the supported peripherals are the digital vision pre-process (DVPP) and network interface collector (NIC). The default profiling interval is 10 ms.


LLC Capacity

Whether to enable profiling for the capacity information of the last level cache (LLC). This switch is mutually exclusive with the LLC bandwidth switch. Only one type of LLC data can be profiled at a time. Sampling Intervals indicates the LLC profiling interval. The value range is [100, 1000]. The default value is 100 (ms).


LLC Bandwidth

Whether to enable profiling for the read and write bandwidths of the LLC. This switch is mutually exclusive with the LLC capacity switch. Only one type of LLC data can be profiled at a time. Sampling Intervals indicates the LLC profiling interval. The value range is [100, 1000]. The default value is 100 (ms).


DDR Profiling

Whether to enable profiling for the read and write bandwidths of the DDR SDRAM. The default setting is OFF.
Master ID indicates the core whose read and write bandwidths are to be profiled. The value range is 0–7. 0–3 correspond to the core IDs of the control CPU. 4–7 correspond to the core IDs of the AI CPU.
Sampling Intervals indicates the DDR profiling interval. The value range is [100, 1000]. The default value is 100 (ms).






 NOTE:   

The performance monitor unit (PMU) is a hardware unit of the CPU. The CPU performance data can be read by accessing related registers.  
DVPP is short for digital vision pre-process.  
NIC is short for network interface controller.  
It is recommended that the DDR and LLC sampling intervals be not greater than the time required for program execution. Otherwise, data cannot be profiled.

Viewing Performance Analysis Results
This topic uses the ResNet18 network as an example to describe how to view the performance analysis results.
After successful profiling, right-click the  ImageClassificationPostProcess  node and choose  profiling result  from the shortcut menu, as shown in  Figure 1. The profiling main page is displayed. You are required to enter the user name and password to log in.
Figure  1  Choosing profiling result

 NOTE:   

If you log in to the profiling main page for the first time, after you click  profiling result, the address bar of the browser will be marked pop-up blocked  . Click  , select  Always allow pop-ups and redirects from [site] , and click  Done. Click  profiling result  again. The profiling main page is displayed.  
You are not advised to open two Mind Studio tab pages on a browser and initiate profiling for the same project. Otherwise, the profiling function may be abnormal.  
The default account for logging in to the profiling main page is the administrator. The user name is  msvpadmin  and the initial password is  Admin12#$. This administrator is able to view performance analysis results and create common users.

summary.html.title: Summary
summary.html.body:
Summary
The  Summary tab displays the collected performance data in tables, covering the following aspects:
You can click    next to a table to export the performance data to an Excel file on the local PC.

Collection Info  area: Displays the data collection start time and end time and the size of the collected performance data, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Collection Info area

Host Info  area: Displays the OS and CPU information about the host where the performance data is collected. For the developer kit form, the host and device are both located on the miniRC. Therefore, the collected data is the basic information about the miniRC, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Host Info area

Device area: 

Displays the information about the device where the performance data is collected, as shown in  Figure 3.
Figure  3  Device area

HiAI Engine  area: Displays the start time and end time of each engine, as shown in  Figure 4.
Figure  4  HiAI Engine area

 NOTE:In the HiAI Engine data, a graph name is in the format  graph+device/host+graphID, and an engine name is in the format  Engine name(thread ID).  


OME area: Displays the time consumed by data input to, inference of, and data output from the model, and details about the running of each operator, including the operator name, operator type, running time, and memory usage, as shown in  Figure 5.
Figure  5  OME area

 NOTE:For the development of the HiAI Engine code, if a thread for invoking the inference engine is created in the code, when Profiling is executed to collect OME data after the project is compiled and executed, the internal thread of the system cannot match the engine. As a result, the  Model Statistic  table in the profiling results cannot display the  Engine Name  information.  


RTS areas: Display the runtime API invocation details and task scheduling information of the Task Scheduler, as shown in  Figure 6.
Figure  6  RTS area

LLC area under  NPU: Displays the read and write bandwidths and hit rate of the LLC of all cores, as shown in  Figure 7.
Figure  7  LLC area under NPU

DDR area: Displays the DDR information, as shown in  Figure 8.
Figure  8  DDR area

Control CPU areas: Display the collected PMU events and hotspot functions of the control CPU, as shown in  Figure 9.
Figure  9  Control CPU areas

Control CPU Usage  area: Display the CPU usage, as shown in  Figure 10.
If the collection time is less than 1s, the diagram is not displayed.
Figure  10  Control CPU Usage area

LLC area under  Control CPU: Displays the total used capacity of the LLC of the control CPU, as shown in  Figure 11.
Figure  11  LLC area under Control CPU

TS CPU  area: Displays the TS CPU usage, as shown in  Figure 12.
If the collection time is less than 1s, the diagram is not displayed.
Figure  12  TS CPU area

AI CPU areas: Display the collected PMU events and hotspot functions of the control CPU, as shown in  Figure 13.
Figure  13  AI CPU area

AI CPU Usage  area: Displays the AI CPU usage, as shown in  Figure 14.
If the collection time is less than 1s, the diagram is not displayed.
Figure  14  AI CPU Usage area

LLC area under AI CPU: Displays the total used capacity of the LLC of the AI CPU, as shown in  Figure 15.
Figure  15  LLC area under AI CPU

AI Core  area: Displays the metrics data calculated based on the AI core PMU events, as well as the AI core status information, as shown in  Figure 16.
Figure  16  AI Core area
Note the following:

 NOTE:Currently, the default events are 0x3, 0x8, 0x9, 0xe, 0x3a, 0x3b, 0x4a, and 0x49. 0x3 indicates the number of executed cube instructions, 0x8 indicates the number of executed vector instructions, 0x9 indicates the number of executed scalar instructions, 0xe indicates the total number of instruction cycles, 0x3a indicates the number of scalar read requests for the UB, 0x3b indicates the number of scalar write requests for the UB, 0x4a indicates the number of cube int instructions, and 0x49 indicates the number of cube FP instructions.The formulas for calculating the AI Core metrics are as follows. The sum of the following ratios is not 1 because there is an inclusion relationship among them.  

total_time  reads the number of task cycles from the PMU_TASK_CYC_CNT register.  Then calculate the time based on the operating frequency.  
mac_fp16_ratio  indicates the ratio of the cycles of cube FP instructions to the cycles of all instructions, which can be obtained by using the formula: mac_fp16_ratio = 1.0 x SUM(0x49)/SUM(PMU_TASK_CYC_CNT)  
mac_int8_ratio  indicates the ratio of the cycles of cube INT instructions to the cycles of all instructions, which can be obtained by using the formula: mac_int8_ratio = 1.0 x SUM(0x4a)/SUM(PMU_TASK_CYC_CNT).  
vec_ratio  indicates the ratio of VEC instructions to all instructions, which can be obtained by using the formula: vec_ratio = 1.0 x SUM(0x8)/SUM(PMU_TASK_CYC_CNT)  
mac_ratio  indicates the occupancy ratio of the cube command (excluding the write request of the special register) in all instructions, which can be obtained by using the formula: mac_ratio = 1.0 x SUM(0x3)/SUM(PMU_TASK_CYC_CNT)  
vec_ratio  indicates the ratio of scalar instructions to all instructions, which can be obtained by using the formula: scalar_ratio = 1.0 x SUM(0x9)/SUM(PMU_TASK_CYC_CNT)  
scalar_ld_ratio  indicates the ratio of the number of read instructions requesting to read the UB to all instructions, which can be obtained by using the formula: scalar_ld_ratio = 1.0 x SUM(0x3a)/SUM(PMU_TASK_CYC_CNT).  
scalar_st_ratio  indicates the ratio of the number of read instructions requesting to write the UB to all instructions, which can be obtained by using the formula: scalar_st_ratio = 1.0 x SUM(0x3b)/SUM(PMU_TASK_CYC_CNT).  



Peripherals area: Displays the task time, number of frames and usage of each DVPP engine, and network TX and RX status of the NIC, as shown in  Figure 17.
Figure  17  Peripherals area

 NOTE:A device in the PCIe card form does not have NIC data. Therefore, NIC profiling should be disabled.

Figure  18  Uplink and downlink data

timeline.html.title: Timeline
timeline.html.body:
Timeline
The  Timeline tab displays the performance timelines of the RTS, HiAI Engine, OME, CCE, and Peripherals, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Performance timelines

The RTS area consists of the following parts:

Thread: timeline information when each thread invokes the runtime APIs, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Thread area

Scheduling: runtime timeline information of tasks scheduled by the Task Scheduler, as shown in  Figure 3.
Figure  3  Scheduling area

Compute: runtime timeline information about the kernel functions on the AI core. You can click the rectangle of each kernel function to view its start runtime and end runtime and the AI core PMU value collected in task-based mode, as shown in  Figure 4.
Figure  4  Compute area

Streams: runtime timeline information about the streams, including the information about the inter-inter-stream synchronization, as shown in  Figure 5.
Figure  5  Streams area



HiAI Engine  area: Displays the start runtime and end runtime of each engine, as shown in  Figure 6.
Figure  6  HiAI Engine area

OME  area: Displays the start runtime, end runtime, and other information of each operator, as shown in  Figure 7.
Figure  7  OME area

Peripherals  area: Displays the peripheral information, including the task time and number of task frames of each engine of the DVPP. The TX and RX network performance of the NIC at each moment is also displayed, as shown in  Figure 8.
Figure  8  Peripherals area
The indicators in the NIC chart are described as follows:

rxPacket/s: Indicates the packet RX rate per second.
rxError rate: Indicates the error rate of received packets.
rxDropped rate: Indicates the packet loss rate of received packets.
Rx Bandwidth efficiency(%): Indicates the bandwidth usage of received packets.
txPacket/s: Indicates the packet TX rate per second.
txError rate: Indicates the error rate of transmitted packets.
txDropped rate: Indicates the packet loss rate of transmitted packets.
Tx Bandwidth efficiency(%): Indicates the bandwidth usage of transmitted packets.

The indicators in the DVPP chart are described as follows:

proc_time: Indicates the engine usage time in each sampling interval.
last_time: Indicates the time when the last task is consumed.
proc_frame: Indicates the number of frames processed by the engine in each sampling interval.
last_frame: Indicates the number of frames of the last task.
proc_utilization: Indicates the time window usage, that is, the accumulated processing time divided by the runtime.
all_utilization: Indicates the average usage, that is, the accumulated processing time divided by the runtime.


LLC area: Displays the read/write bandwidth and hit ratio of the LLC at each moment, including the LLC capacity used by the control CPU and AI CPU at each moment, as shown in  Figure 9.
Figure  9  LLC area

DDR area: Displays the DDR SDRAM information.
Figure  10  DDR area

RTStrack area: Displays the uplink and downlink data of each AI core task, as shown in  Figure 11.
Figure  11  RTStrack area

 NOTE:   

The time blocks in all Timeline charts can be zoomed in or out by using the scroll wheel. You can also find the zoom in, zoom out, and restoration buttons in the upper right corner.  
After zooming in, you can press and hold the left mouse button and drag a time block to view the detailed information.

control-cpu-function.html.body:
Control CPU Function
As long as  Control CPU Profiling  is enabled in the  Hardware configuration area, the  Control CPU Function  tab page is generated. The top functions of the control CPU during profiling are ranked by  Cycles by default, as shown in  Figure 1.
You can click    next to the table to export the data to an Excel file on the local PC.
Figure  1  Control CPU Function tab page
Configure the  Control CPU Binary/Symbol Search  and  Control CPU C/C++ Source Search  paths on the  Configuration  tab page. On the  Control CPU Function  tab page, select  Module/Fucntion/Callstack  in the  Grouping  area, double-click the function name to jump to the source code of the corresponding function. 

 NOTE:~/tools  is the default  toolpath  setting, which can be customized during Mind Studio installation. You can view the value of  toolpath in the  scripts/env.conf  file. You can run the  find / -name 'env.conf'  command to view the location of the  env.conf  file in the  script directory.  

The procedure is as follows:

Go to the  Control CPU Function  tab page, select  Module/Fucntion/Callstack, view the path of the binary application file to which the function belongs on the device, and record the path.
For example, in the example shown in  Figure 2, the binary application file  libcrypto.so.1.1  is stored in the  /usr/lib64  directory on the device.
Figure  2  Viewing the path of the binary application file

Log in to the Mind Studio server as the Mind Studio installation user and obtain the aarch64-linux-gnu-objdump and aarch64-linux-gnu-addr2line tools from the  ~/tools/che/ddk/ddk/toolchains/aarch64-linux-gcc6.3/bin  directory. Run the following commands:
./aarch64-linux-gnu-objdump -S  binary file path: Obtains the address of the assembly instructions.
./aarch64-linux-gnu-addr2line -ie libcrypto.so.1.1  Specific assembly instruction address: Obtains the source code path.

 NOTE:   

The binary file must contain the symbol information (not stripped). That is, the debug version compiled by using the -g  option is used. Otherwise, the source code path cannot be obtained after the  addr2line command is executed.  
objdump and addr2line are third-party open source tools. You can look up the parameters of them yourself.  
For Mind Studio on the developer board, you can obtain the aarch64-linux-gnu-objdump and aarch64-linux-gnu-addr2line tools from the  /usr/bin  directory on the Mind Studio server.  



Go to the  Configuration  tab and click  Modify  next to  Control CPU Binary/Symbol Search. Set the path to the  tools path of the Mind Studio installation directory on the server, for example,  /home/ascend/tools/demo.
Figure  3  Modifying the path 

Similarly, click  Modify  next to  Control CPU C/C++ Source Search. Set the path to the  tools path of the Mind Studio installation directory on the server, for example,  /home/ascend/tools/demo.

Create the binary file path recorded in  1  in the path configured in  3. Create the source code path recorded in  2  in the path configured in  4.
For example, create the  usr/lib64  directory in  ~/tools/demo.

 NOTE:   

If the binary file path and source code path are not in the standard Linux absolute path format, directly save the binary file and source code in the root directory of the configuration path described in Step 3.  
If the binary file path and source code path contain invalid characters such as [ \ ' ; * ? ~ ` ! @ # $ % ^ & + = ) (  { } ] | ", the function cannot be used.  



Copy the binary files on the device side to the directory created in  5, for example,  ~/tools/demo/usr/lib64.

Go to the  Control CPU Function  tab and double-click any function in the red frame. The assembly code and source code corresponding to the function is displayed.
Figure  4  Jumping to the source code



 NOTE:Ensure that the path is the  tools path in the home directory of the Mind Studio installation user.

full-process-profiling-in-command-line-m.body:
Full-Process Profiling in Command Line Mode
To analyze performance data in command line mode, log in to the Mind Studio server as the Mind Studio installation user and run the commands in the script  ~/tools/profiler/analysis/msvp/host/bin64/hiprof.pyc  to profile performance data. After successful profiling, you can view the performance analysis results in the command line window.

 NOTE:~/tools  is the default  toolpath  setting, which can be customized during Mind Studio installation. You can view the value of  toolpath in the  scripts/env.conf  file. You can run the  find / -name 'env.conf'  command to view the location of the  env.conf  file in the  script directory.  

Profiling performance data
The following uses the data on process orchestration as an example to describe how to profile the performance data.

Log in to the Mind Studio server as the Mind Studio installation user.
Go to the directory where the  hiprof.pyc  script is stored, for example  ~/tools/profiler/analysis/msvp/host/bin64.
Profile software and hardware data in sample-based mode and task-based mode respectively.
In the following commands, change the value of  *_dir  as required. Make sure that the Mind Studio installation user can access this directory.  --ai_core_profiling_mode=sample-based  indicates that data is profiled in sample-based mode. Replace  x.x.x.x  with the IP address of the server where the host is located.
After the commands are executed, the configuration parameters in the commands are saved in the  sample.ini  file by default. The file is saved in the directory specified by the  result_dir  parameter. For details about the configuration, see  sample.ini File.

Commands for profiling all software and hardware data in sample-based mode.
python hiprof.pyc --ip_address=x.x.x.x --ddk_dir=~/tools/che/ddk/ddk --app=/projects/MIND/out/main --app_dir=/projects/MIND/ --umode=MIND --result_dir=/home/ascend/tools/out --peripheral_profiling=nic,dvpp  --ai_cpu_profiling=on --RTS_Profiling=on --ai_core_profiling_mode=sample-based --ai_core_profiling=on --HIAI_Engine_Profiling=on --OME_Profiling=on --ctrl_cpu_profiling=on --profiling_mode=online --llc_bandwidth=on --ddr_profiling=on

Commands for profiling all software and hardware data in task-based mode.
python hiprof.pyc --ip_address=x.x.x.x --ddk_dir=~/tools/che/ddk/ddk --app=/projects/MIND/out/main --app_dir=/projects/MIND/ --umode=MIND --result_dir=/home/ascend/tools/out --peripheral_profiling=nic,dvpp --ai_cpu_profiling=on --RTS_Profiling=on --ai_core_profiling_mode=task-based --ai_core_profiling=on --HIAI_Engine_Profiling=on --OME_Profiling=on --ctrl_cpu_profiling=on --profiling_mode=online --llc_bandwidth=on --ddr_profiling=on

Commands with parameters for profiling data in task-based mode.
python hiprof.pyc --ip_address=x.x.x.x --ddk_dir=~/tools/che/ddk/ddk --app_dir=/projects/MIND --umode=MIND --result_dir=/home/ascend/tools/out  --ai_cpu_profiling=on --RTS_Profiling=on --ai_core_profiling=on --ctrl_cpu_profiling=on -- /projects/MIND/perfor/main Performace_Freespace_Road_FP16_1B_AIPP.json

Parameter

Description

Mandatory or Not

Yes

Yes

Yes

Yes

Yes

No

No


HIAI_Engine_Profiling

Whether to enable profiling for HiAI Engine. The default setting is OFF.

No


peripheral_profiling_interval

Peripheral profiling interval. The value range is [1, 1000]. The default value is 10.

No

Peripheral profiling mode: dvpp, nic, or both. A comma (,) must be used to separate them. This parameter is left blank by default.

No

Whether to enable profiling for the control CPU. The default setting is OFF.

No

Whether to enable profiling for the TS CPU. The default setting is OFF.

No


ai_cpu_profiling

Whether to enable profiling for the AI CPU. The default setting is OFF.

No

Whether to enable profiling for the AI core. The default setting is OFF.

No

AI core profiling mode. The value can be task-based or sample-based. In task-based mode, data is profiled by task. In sample-based mode, data is profiled by sample. The default setting is task-based.

No

No


RTS_Profiling

Whether to enable RTS profiling. 

No

Directory of the result file. If it does not exist, create it. If it exists, change it to .old. The path must be an absolute path.
The result_dir path is used to store profiling results. Ensure that the Mind Studio installation user has the read and write permission on the path. You are advised to set this path to the directory under ~/tools/ or /projects/.

No

No

Imports profiling result file to the database by calling mvsp_import.pyc. You need to configure the project file path. A profiling result file must be stored in a directory under Home directory of the Mind Studio installation user/tools/. Otherwise, the file cannot be imported. This parameter is not saved in sample.ini.

No

In the python hiprof.pyc command line, contain the report parameter and add the absolute path of the profiling result to be printed. for example, python hiprof.pyc --report /projects/test/profiling_output/

No


llc_bandwidth

Whether to enable read/write bandwidth profiling for the LLC. The default setting is OFF. This parameter is mutually exclusive with llc_capacity. Only one type of LLC data can be collected at a time.

No


llc_capacity

Used capacity of the LLC. The default setting is OFF. This parameter is mutually exclusive with llc_bandwidth. Only one type of LLC data can be collected at a time.

No


llc_interval

LLC profiling interval. This parameter is mandatory if the interval is required. The value range is [100, 1000]. The default value is 100 (ms).

No


ddr_profiling

Whether to enable profiling for the DDR SDRAM. 

No


ddr_master_id

Whether to enable read/write bandwidth profiling for the AI CPU and control CPU core. This parameter is left blank by default. The value range is 0–7. 0–3 correspond to the core IDs of the control CPU. 4–7 correspond to the core IDs of the AI CPU.

No


ddr_interval

DDR profiling interval. This parameter is mandatory if the interval is required. The value range is [100, 1000]. The default value is 100 (ms).

No


all

Whether to enable profiling for all performance. The default value is OFF.

No


help

Help information

No

Ensure that all paths of  result_dir  have the 750 permission.  
The input format of the operators with parameters is:  --  Path where the app file is stored in the UI host (including the app name)  para1 para2. (para1 para2  are the parameters of the app) For example: -- /projects/CCE/out/main para1 para2  If  Path where the app file is stored in the UI host (including the app name)  para1 para2  is added to the command line for performance data profiling, this parameter must be placed at the end of the command line and the  --app  parameter must be deleted from the command line, otherwise, a parsing error occurs.  
It is recommended that the DDR and LLC sampling intervals be not greater than the time required for program execution. Otherwise, data cannot be profiled.  
If the profiling time is less than 1s, the  Control CPU Usage,  AI CPU Usage, and  TS CPU Usage  charts are not displayed.

resetting-the-password-for-connecting-to.body:
Resetting the Password for Connecting to the Redis Service
For security purpose, you are advised to reset the password for connecting to the Redis service periodically (for example, every 90 days). The default password is  Huawei12#$.

Log in to the Mind Studio server as the Mind Studio installation user.
Go to the  tools/profiler  directory and run the following command to reset the password:
dir  indicates the installation path of Profiling, and  ~  must be replaced with the home directory of the Mind Studio installation user.
./install_profiling.sh --reset_redis_pwd --dir=~/tools/profiler

 NOTE:~/tools  is the default  toolpath  setting, which can be customized during Mind Studio installation. You can view the value of  toolpath in the  scripts/env.conf  file. You can run the  find / -name 'env.conf'  command to view the location of the  env.conf  file in the  script directory.  

Enter the new password twice as prompted, as shown in  Figure 1.
A new password must meet the following requirements:

The password must contain at least six characters.
A password is a combination of at least two types of the following:
At least one lowercase letter
At least one uppercase letter
At least one digit
At least one space or one of the following special characters: ` ~ ! @ # $ % ^ & * ( ) - _ = + \ | [ { } ] ; : ' " ,  / ?



Figure  1  Entering the new password
If the information shown in  Figure 2  is displayed, the password is reset successfully.
Figure  2  Password reset successfully

instructions-2.html.title: Instructions
instructions-2.html.body:
Instructions
According to  Table 1, the following describes how to obtain the exception information in three scenarios.
Obtaining the Latest Exception of Each Device

In the Mind Studio main menu, choose  Tools > Black Box > Latest.
Enter the IP address of the target host, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Host IP configuration dialog box

The  Download black box exceptions dialog box is displayed, showing the download progress, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Download black box exceptions dialog box

After the exception information is transferred, the message indicating that the exception.zip package is being downloaded. The .zip package is named after the timestamp. Send it to Huawei engineers for analysis.


Obtaining the Exceptions about All Devices

In the Mind Studio main menu, choose  Tools > Black Box > All.
Enter the IP address of the target host, as shown in  Figure 1.
The  Download black box exceptions dialog box is displayed, showing the download progress, as shown in  Figure 2.
After the exception information is transferred, the message indicating that the exception.zip package is being downloaded. The .zip package is named after the timestamp. Send it to Huawei engineers for analysis.

Obtaining the Latest  N  Exceptions of a Specified Device

In the Mind Studio main menu, choose  Tools > Black Box > Filtered.
Enter the IP address of the target host, as shown in  Figure 1.
A dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 3. Select the ID of the abnormal device and enter the number of the latest exceptions to be obtained.
Figure  3  Black Box dialog box

The  Download black box exceptions dialog box is displayed, showing the download progress, as shown in  Figure 2.

After the exception information is transferred, the message indicating that the exception.zip package is being downloaded. The .zip package is named after the timestamp. Send it to Huawei engineers for analysis.
